<p>The Australian Labor Party (ALP) includes a variety of networks and associations that connect members, advocate for issues, and contribute to the party’s policy development. The national platform currently mandates or encourages state branches to formally establish these groups along with calling for generalised interest groups known as policy action caucuses.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-76"><a href="#cite_note-76"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Examples of such groups include the Labor Environment Action Network,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-77"><a href="#cite_note-77"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/LGBTQ_wing" title="LGBTQ wing">LGBTQ wing</a> Rainbow Labor,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-78"><a href="#cite_note-78"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ANUPressChapter28_79-0"><a href="#cite_note-ANUPressChapter28-79"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Labor For Choice, the <a href="/wiki/Women%27s_wing" title="Women's wing">women's wing</a> Labor Women's Network,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-80"><a href="#cite_note-80"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Labor for Drug Law Reform<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-81"><a href="#cite_note-81"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Labor for Refugees,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-82"><a href="#cite_note-82"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Labor for Housing,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-83"><a href="#cite_note-83"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Labor Teachers Network,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-84"><a href="#cite_note-84"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Aboriginal Labor Network,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-85"><a href="#cite_note-85"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and recently, Labor Enabled – the action group for Disability Advocacy<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-86"><a href="#cite_note-86"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>These groups operate under different names across states and territories and are categorized into <b>equity groups</b>, which focus on representation based on identity or shared characteristics, and <b>policy-focused groups</b>, which emphasize thematic advocacy. In Queensland, these networks are formally referred to as <i>Equity Groups</i> and <i>Associations</i>, which are distinct entities.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-QLDLaborRules_87-0"><a href="#cite_note-QLDLaborRules-87"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other states use terms such as forums, caucuses, or committees.
</p>

<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Ideology_and_factions">Ideology and factions</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Australian_Labor_Party&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Ideology and factions"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Labor's constitution has long stated: "The Australian Labor Party is a democratic socialist party and has the objective of the democratic <a href="/wiki/Social_ownership" title="Social ownership">socialisation</a> of industry, production, distribution and exchange, to the extent necessary to eliminate exploitation and other anti-social features in these fields".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Australian_Labor_Party-2015_61-1"><a href="#cite_note-Australian_Labor_Party-2015-61"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This "socialist objective" was introduced in 1921, but was later qualified by two further objectives: "maintenance of and support for a competitive non-monopolistic private sector" and "the right to own private property". Labor governments have not attempted the "democratic socialisation" of any industry since the 1940s, when the <a href="/wiki/Chifley_government" title="Chifley government">Chifley government</a> failed to nationalise the private banks, and in fact have <a href="/wiki/Privatization" title="Privatization">privatised</a> several industries such as aviation and banking.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-102"><a href="#cite_note-102"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-103"><a href="#cite_note-103"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-104"><a href="#cite_note-104"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-105"><a href="#cite_note-105"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>97<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Factions">Factions</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Australian_Labor_Party&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Factions"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1257001546" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><table class="infobox vcard"><tbody><tr><th class="infobox-above" colspan="2" style="font-size: 125%;"><div style="padding-top:0.3em; padding-bottom:0.3em; border-top:2px solid #F00011; border-bottom:2px solid #F00011; line-height: 1;"><div class="fn org">Parliamentary caucus seats<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></div> </div></th></tr><tr><td class="infobox-image logo" colspan="2" style="padding-top:.4em;padding-bottom:.3em;"><span class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Frameless"><a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg"><img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="185" data-file-width="360" decoding="async" height="103" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg/250px-Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg/330px-Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg/400px-Australian_Labor_Party_Federal_Caucus.svg.png 2x" width="200"/></a></span></td></tr><tr><th class="infobox-label" scope="row" style="line-height:1.3em;"><a href="/wiki/Labor_Right" title="Labor Right">Labor Right</a></th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height:1.3em;"><div style="width: 100px;"><span class="nowrap">53 / 103</span><div style="box-sizing: border-box; border: 1px solid #aaa; height: 1.15em; position: relative;"><div style="background-color: #FF0000; color:inherit; width: 51%; height: 100%;"></div></div></div>
</td></tr><tr><th class="infobox-label" scope="row" style="line-height:1.3em;"><a href="/wiki/Labor_Left" title="Labor Left">Labor Left</a></th><td class="infobox-data" style="line-height:1.3em;"><div style="width: 100px;"><span class="nowrap">48 / 103</span><div style="box-sizing: border-box; border: 1px solid #aaa; height: 1.15em; position: relative;"><div style="background-color: #B00D0D; color:inherit; width: 47%; height: 100%;"></div></div></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The Labor Party has always had a left wing and a right wing; however, since 1989, it has been organised into formal factions.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Chen-2019_106-0"><a href="#cite_note-Chen-2019-106"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The two largest factional groupings are the <a href="/wiki/Labor_Left" title="Labor Left">Labor Left</a>, who are supportive of <a href="/wiki/Democratic_socialism" title="Democratic socialism">democratic socialist</a> ideals, and the <a href="/wiki/Labor_Right" title="Labor Right">Labor Right</a> who generally support <a href="/wiki/Social_democracy" title="Social democracy">social democratic</a> traditions. The national factional groupings are themselves divided into formal factions, primarily state-based such as Centre Unity in New South Wales and Labor Forum in Queensland.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Chen-2019_106-1"><a href="#cite_note-Chen-2019-106"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some trade unions are affiliated with the Labor Party and are also factionally aligned. Important unions supporting the right faction are the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Workers%27_Union" title="Australian Workers' Union">Australian Workers' Union</a> (AWU), the <a href="/wiki/Shop,_Distributive_and_Allied_Employees_Association" title="Shop, Distributive and Allied Employees Association">Shop, Distributive and Allied Employees Association</a> (SDA) and the <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Transport_Workers_Union_of_Australia" title="Transport Workers Union of Australia">Transport Workers Union of Australia</a> (TWU).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Marin-Guzman-2018_107-0"><a href="#cite_note-Marin-Guzman-2018-107"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Important unions supporting the left include the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Manufacturing_Workers_Union" title="Australian Manufacturing Workers Union">Australian Manufacturing Workers Union</a> (AMWU), <a href="/wiki/United_Workers_Union" title="United Workers Union">United Workers Union</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Construction,_Forestry_and_Maritime_Employees_Union" title="Construction, Forestry and Maritime Employees Union">Construction, Forestry and Maritime Employees Union</a> (CFMEU) and the <a href="/wiki/Community_and_Public_Sector_Union" title="Community and Public Sector Union">Community and Public Sector Union</a> (CPSU).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Marin-Guzman-2018_107-1"><a href="#cite_note-Marin-Guzman-2018-107"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>

<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Donors">Donors</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Australian_Labor_Party&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Donors"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1236090951" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">See also: <a href="/wiki/Political_funding_in_Australia" title="Political funding in Australia">Political funding in Australia</a></div>
<p>In 2023/24, state and federal branches of Labor reported $67.5 million in donations. Labor's largest donation was $1m from <a href="/wiki/Anthony_Pratt_(businessman)" title="Anthony Pratt (businessman)">Anthony Pratt</a>. Other large donors were unions and gambling companies.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-109"><a href="#cite_note-109"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Labor Party also receives undisclosed funding through several methods, such as "associated entities". <a href="/wiki/John_Curtin_House" title="John Curtin House">John Curtin House</a>, Industry 2020, IR21 and the Happy Wanderers Club are entities which have been used to funnel donations to the Labor Party without disclosing the source.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-110"><a href="#cite_note-110"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-111"><a href="#cite_note-111"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-112"><a href="#cite_note-112"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>103<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-113"><a href="#cite_note-113"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A 2019 report found that the Labor Party received $33,000 from pro-gun groups during the 2011–2018 periods compared to $82,000 received by the Coalition.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Knowles-2019_114-0"><a href="#cite_note-Knowles-2019-114"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>105<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>

<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Notes">Notes</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Australian_Labor_Party&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Notes"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1239543626">.mw-parser-output .reflist{margin-bottom:0.5em;list-style-type:decimal}@media screen{.mw-parser-output .reflist{font-size:90%}}.mw-parser-output .reflist .references{font-size:100%;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:inherit}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns-2{column-width:30em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns-3{column-width:25em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns{margin-top:0.3em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns ol{margin-top:0}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns li{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .reflist-upper-alpha{list-style-type:upper-alpha}.mw-parser-output .reflist-upper-roman{list-style-type:upper-roman}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-alpha{list-style-type:lower-alpha}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-greek{list-style-type:lower-greek}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-roman{list-style-type:lower-roman}</style><div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">According to <i><a href="/wiki/The_Australian_Worker" title="The Australian Worker">The Australian Worker</a></i>, in 1918 the state parties comprised the Political Labor League (New South Wales), the Queensland Labor Party, the United Labor Party (South Australia), the Workers' Political Labor League (Tasmania), the Political Labor Council (Victoria), and the Australian Labor Federation (Western Australia).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-14"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, according to the <i><a href="/wiki/South_Australian_Register" title="South Australian Register">South Australian Register</a></i>, the state parties in New South Wales, South Australia, and Victoria had already adopted the standardised name by 1917.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">In 1954, Labor MP <a href="/wiki/Ted_Johnson_(politician)" title="Ted Johnson (politician)">Ted Johnson</a> complained in the <a href="/wiki/Parliament_of_Western_Australia" title="Parliament of Western Australia">Parliament of Western Australia</a> that both <i><a href="/wiki/Hansard" title="Hansard">Hansard</a></i> and the daily newspapers were still using the spelling "Labour".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-18"><a href="#cite_note-18"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As late as the 1980s, historian <a href="/wiki/Finlay_Crisp" title="Finlay Crisp">Finlay Crisp</a> used the spelling "Labour" in academic works about the party.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-19"><a href="#cite_note-19"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-20"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-65"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Queensland has maintained a <a href="/wiki/Unicameralism" title="Unicameralism">unicameral legislature</a> since 1922.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-66"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Tasmania uses a semi-proportional system and thus TPP is not calculated.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-67"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-67">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Tasmania elects <a href="/wiki/Tasmanian_Legislative_Council" title="Tasmanian Legislative Council">legislative council</a> representatives on a periodic basis, with elections held almost every year.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-68"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-68">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The ACT uses a semi-proportional system and thus TPP is not calculated.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-69"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-69">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The ACT has a <a href="/wiki/Unicameralism" title="Unicameralism">unicameral</a> parliament.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-70"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-70">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Northern Territory has a <a href="/wiki/Unicameralism" title="Unicameralism">unicameral</a> parliament.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-108"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-108">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Whitlam" title="Whitlam">Whitlam</a>-led party became the <a href="/wiki/Opposition_(Australia)" title="Opposition (Australia)">Opposition</a> after the <a href="/wiki/Governor-General_of_Australia" title="Governor-General of Australia">Governor-General</a>, <a href="/wiki/John_Kerr_(governor-general)" title="John Kerr (governor-general)">John Kerr</a>, dismissed it during the <a href="/wiki/1975_Australian_constitutional_crisis" title="1975 Australian constitutional crisis">1975 constitutional crisis</a>, despite Labor maintaining a majority in the <a href="/wiki/Australian_House_of_Representatives" title="Australian House of Representatives">House of Representatives</a>.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>

Find History¶

In [50]:
## Find History
# Find the section containing the History content
history_section = soup.find("span", {"id": "History"})

# If the History section exists, get its content
if history_section:
    
    # Get the parent section (usually an <h2> tag)
    history_heading = history_section.find_parent("h2")
    
    # Initialize a list to store content paragraphs
    history_content = []
    
    # Get all sibling elements until the next <h2> tag and extract text
    next_sibling = history_heading.find_next_sibling()
    while next_sibling and next_sibling.name != "h2":
        if next_sibling.name == "p":
            history_content.append(next_sibling.get_text())
        next_sibling = next_sibling.find_next_sibling()
    
    print("History Content:")
    for paragraph in history_content:
        print(paragraph.strip())  # Strip to remove leading and trailing whitespaces
else:
    print("History section not found.")

## Find Main Content
# Extract the key sections of the page
sections = soup.find_all("h2")
for section in sections:
    section_title = section.text
    section_content_tag = section.find_next("p")
    if section_content_tag:
        section_content = section_content_tag.text
        print("Section Title:", section_title)
        print("Section Content:", section_content)
        print()

Section Title: Contents
Section Content: 


Section Title: Name and spelling
Section Content: In standard Australian English, the word labour is spelt with a u. However, the political party uses the spelling Labor, without a u. There was originally no standardised spelling of the party's name, with Labor and Labour both in common usage. According to Ross McMullin, who wrote an official history of the Labor Party, the title page of the proceedings of the Federal Conference used the spelling "Labor" in 1902, "Labour" in 1905 and 1908, and then "Labor" from 1912 onwards.[12] In 1908, James Catts put forward a motion at the Federal Conference that "the name of the party be the Australian Labour Party", which was carried by 22 votes to 2. A separate motion recommending state branches adopt the name was defeated. There was no uniformity of party names until 1918 when the Federal party resolved that state branches should adopt the name "Australian Labor Party", now spelt without a u. Each state branch had previously used a different name, due to their different origins.[13][a]


Section Title: History
Section Content: The Australian Labor Party has its origins in the Labour parties founded in the 1890s in the Australian colonies prior to federation. Labor tradition ascribes the founding of Queensland Labour to a meeting of striking pastoral workers under a ghost gum tree (the Tree of Knowledge) in Barcaldine, Queensland in 1891. The 1891 shearers' strike is credited as being one of the factors for the formation of the Australian Labor Party. On 9 September 1892 the Manifesto of the Queensland Labour Party was read out under the well known Tree of Knowledge at Barcaldine following the Great Shearers' Strike.[24] The State Library of Queensland now holds the manifesto;[25][26] in 2008 the historic document was added to UNESCO's Memory of the World Australian Register[27] and, in 2009, the document was added to UNESCO's Memory of the World International Register.[28] The Balmain, New South Wales branch of the party claims to be the oldest in Australia. However, the Scone Branch has a receipt for membership fees for the Labour Electoral League dated April 1891. This predates the Balmain claim. This can be attested in the Centenary of the ALP book.[citation needed] Labour as a parliamentary party dates from 1891 in New South Wales and South Australia, 1893 in Queensland, and later in the other colonies.


Section Title: National platform
Section Content: The policy of the Australian Labor Party is contained in its National Platform, which is approved by delegates to Labor's National Conference, held every three years. According to the Labor Party's website, "The Platform is the result of a rigorous and constructive process of consultation, spanning the nation and including the cooperation and input of state and territory policy committees, local branches, unions, state and territory governments, and individual Party members. The Platform provides the policy foundation from which we can continue to work towards the election of a federal Labor government."[58]


Section Title: Party structure
Section Content: The Australian Labor Party National Executive is the party's chief administrative authority, subject only to Labor's national conference. The executive is responsible for organising the triennial national conference; carrying out the decisions of the conference; interpreting the national constitution, the national platform and decisions of the national conference; and directing federal members.[59]


Section Title: Ideology and factions
Section Content: Labor's constitution has long stated: "The Australian Labor Party is a democratic socialist party and has the objective of the democratic socialisation of industry, production, distribution and exchange, to the extent necessary to eliminate exploitation and other anti-social features in these fields".[59] This "socialist objective" was introduced in 1921, but was later qualified by two further objectives: "maintenance of and support for a competitive non-monopolistic private sector" and "the right to own private property". Labor governments have not attempted the "democratic socialisation" of any industry since the 1940s, when the Chifley government failed to nationalise the private banks, and in fact have privatised several industries such as aviation and banking.[94][95][96][97]


Section Title: Election results
Section Content: In 2023/24, state and federal branches of Labor reported $67.5 million in donations. Labor's largest donation was $1m from Anthony Pratt. Other large donors were unions and gambling companies.[100]


Section Title: Donors
Section Content: In 2023/24, state and federal branches of Labor reported $67.5 million in donations. Labor's largest donation was $1m from Anthony Pratt. Other large donors were unions and gambling companies.[100]
